The superposed solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A Temperature Curve Specified for the Bottom and the Top insulated
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The boundary condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r,z,t)$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(r,0,t)=f(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By superposing the separable solutions, we have, for 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in[0,L+h]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in[0,r_{0}]$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(r,z,t)=\intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}\left[A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)+B_{\lambda}Y_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)\right]C_{\omega}\cos\omega ze^{-(\omega^{2}+\lambda^{2})\kappa t}d\omega d\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|u(0,z,t)\right|<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\lambda}=0$
\end_inset

.
 So we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u(r,z,t) & =\intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)C_{\omega}\cos\omega ze^{-(\omega^{2}+\lambda^{2})\kappa t}d\omega d\lambda
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution must satisfy the boundary condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u(r,0,t) & =f(t)\\
\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}\left(r,L+h,t\right) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 2nd equation stems from the fact that the top of the cylinder is insulated
 from heat transmission.
 It implies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)\omega C_{\omega}\sin\omega\left(L+h\right)e^{-(\omega^{2}+\lambda^{2})\kappa t}d\omega d\lambda=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since this equation holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sin\omega\left(L+h\right) & =0\\
\omega\left(L+h\right) & =n\pi
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0,1,2,\dots$
\end_inset

.
 Hence we'd rather have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u(r,z,t) & =\intop_{0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)C_{n}\cos\frac{n\pi z}{L+h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\right)^{2}\kappa t-\lambda^{2}\kappa t\right]d\lambda\\
u(r,0,t) & =\left[\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa t}d\lambda\right]\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}C_{n}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\right)^{2}\kappa t\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(\kappa t)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}C_{n}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\right)^{2}\kappa t\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exact form of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\kappa t)$
\end_inset

 is to be determined by the determination of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n},n=0,1,2,\dots$
\end_inset

.
 It follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left[\frac{f(t)}{g(\kappa t)}\right]=-\intop_{0}^{\infty}\lambda A_{\lambda}J_{1}\left(\lambda r\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa t}d\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equating the LHS to 0 gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{0}^{\infty}\lambda A_{\lambda}J_{1}\left(\lambda r\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa t}d\lambda=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This only plausible choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}=0$
\end_inset

.
 So the solution is similar to that in the 1D case:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(r,z,t)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}D_{n}\cos\frac{n\pi z}{L+h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\right)^{2}\kappa t\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{n}=\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left[f\left(\frac{\cdot}{\kappa}\right)\right]\left(\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Temperature curve specified at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r,z,t)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r\leq r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq z\leq h$
\end_inset

 satisfies, for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\leq r_{0}<r_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u(r,z,t) & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}D_{n}\cos\frac{n\pi(z+L)}{L+h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\right)^{2}\kappa t\right]\\
D_{n} & =\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left[f\left(\frac{\cdot}{\kappa}\right)\right]\left(\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,t)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}D_{n}\cos\frac{n\pi(z+L)}{L+h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{n\pi}{L+h}\right)^{2}\kappa t\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in[r_{0},r_{1}]$
\end_inset

, we assume
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(r,z,t)=\intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)C_{\omega}\cos\omega ze^{-(\omega^{2}+\lambda^{2})\kappa't}d\omega d\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should satisfy the condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}(r,0,t) & =0\\
\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}(r,h,t) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiation gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}=-\intop_{0}^{\infty}\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)\omega C_{\omega}\sin\omega ze^{-(\omega^{2}+\lambda^{2})\kappa't}d\omega d\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}(r,0,t)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}(r,h,t)=0$
\end_inset

 implies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sin\omega h & =0\\
\omega h & =m\pi\\
\omega & =\frac{m\pi}{h}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u(r,z,t) & =\left[\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda\right]\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}C_{m}\cos\frac{m\pi z}{h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{m\pi}{h}\right)^{2}\kappa't\right]\\
u(r_{0},z,t) & =\left[\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda\right]\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}C_{m}\cos\frac{m\pi z}{h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{m\pi}{h}\right)^{2}\kappa't\right]\\
 & =\left[\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda\right]\left\{ \sum_{m=0}^{\infty}C_{m}\cos\frac{m\pi z}{h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{m\pi}{h}\right)^{2}\kappa't\right]\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can expand 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,t)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in[0,h]$
\end_inset

 as a cosine series:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z,t)=\frac{a_{0,t}}{2}+\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}a_{m,t}\cos\left(\frac{2\pi mz}{h}\right)\label{eq:ghtynjyyuk}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Fourier coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r_{0},z,t)$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a'_{n,t} & =\frac{2}{h}\intop_{0}^{h}u(r_{0},z,t)\cos\frac{2\pi nz}{h}dz\\
 & =\left[\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda\right]\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\left\{ \exp\left[-\left(\frac{m\pi}{h}\right)^{2}\kappa't\right]\frac{2}{h}\intop_{0}^{h}C_{m}\cos\frac{m\pi z}{h}\cos\frac{2\pi nz}{h}dz\right\} \\
 & =\left[\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda\right]\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\left\{ \exp\left[-\left(\frac{m\pi}{h}\right)^{2}\kappa't\right]C_{m}\left(1_{\{m=2n\}}1_{\{m\neq0\}}+1_{\{m=n=0\}}2\right)\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a'_{0,t} & =2C_{0}\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda\\
a'_{n,t} & =C_{2n}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{2n\pi}{h}\right)^{2}\kappa't\right]\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(r_{0},z,t)=\left[\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda\right]\left\{ C_{0}+\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}C_{2n}\cos\frac{2n\pi z}{h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{2n\pi}{h}\right)^{2}\kappa't\right]\right\} \label{eq:5yvhb6b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equating the Fourier coefficients in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ghtynjyyuk"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5yvhb6b"

\end_inset

, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C_{0}\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda & =\frac{a_{0,t}}{2}\\
C_{2n}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{2n\pi}{h}\right)^{2}\kappa't\right]\intop_{0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda}J_{0}\left(\lambda r_{0}\right)e^{-\lambda^{2}\kappa't}d\lambda & =a_{n,t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Steady-State temperature distribution of a Cylinder
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the divergence of the temperature gradient is 0 everywhere, including
 on the boundary of the object, the temperature distribution has reached
 a steady state.
 Clearly this steady-state distribution is described by the Laplace equation.
 For a cylinder, the solution is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(r,\phi,z)=\left[AJ_{m}\left(\lambda r\right)+BY_{m}\left(\lambda r\right)\right]\left[C\cos m\phi+D\sin m\phi\right]\left[Ee^{-\lambda z}+Fe^{\lambda z}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The temperature must be finite everywhere in the cylinder, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $B=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F=0$
\end_inset

.
 If the temperature distribution is axially symmetric, then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

.
 In these scenarios, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(r,z)=AJ_{0}\left(\lambda r\right)e^{-\lambda z}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, this solution cannot describe a scenario where the temperature
 has no radial dependence.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 only depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, then the Laplace equation gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}u=\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=Cz+D
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Attempted Solutions to 2D & 3D diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
2D Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now in 2D we consider solutions of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x,y,t)=f(\eta)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}}{\kappa t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}=\frac{2x}{\kappa t}f'(\eta)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}=f''(\eta)\left(\frac{2x}{\kappa t}\right)^{2}+f'(\eta)\frac{2}{\kappa t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\kappa\nabla^{2}u & =\kappa f''(\eta)\cdot4\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}}{\kappa^{2}t^{2}}+\kappa f'(\eta)\frac{4}{\kappa t}\\
 & =f''(\eta)\frac{4\eta}{t}+f'(\eta)\frac{4}{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}=-\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}}{\kappa t^{2}}f'(\eta)=-\frac{\eta}{t}f'(\eta)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting these expressions into the PDE, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
4\eta f''(\eta)+4f'(\eta)=-\eta f'(\eta)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g=f'(\eta)$
\end_inset

, then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
4\eta g'+4g & =-\eta g\\
4\eta g' & =-(\eta+4)g\\
\frac{dg}{g} & =\left(-\frac{1}{4}-\frac{1}{\eta}\right)d\eta\\
\ln\left|g\right| & =-\frac{\eta}{4}-\ln(\eta)+C'\\
g & =A\frac{e^{-\eta/4}}{\eta}\\
f & =A\intop_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}\frac{e^{-\mu/4}}{\mu}d\mu+C\\
 & =A\intop_{\eta_{0}/4}^{\eta/4}\frac{e^{-\mu}}{4\mu}4d\mu+C\\
 & =A\intop_{\eta_{0}/4}^{\eta/4}\frac{e^{-\mu}}{\mu}d\mu+C
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}>4$
\end_inset

 so that we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\eta)=A\intop_{1}^{\eta/4}\frac{e^{-\mu}}{\mu}d\mu+C
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to0$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}}{\kappa t}\to\infty
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{1}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-\mu}}{\mu}d\mu<\intop_{1}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-\mu}}{\sqrt{\mu}}d\mu<\sqrt{\pi}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\to0$
\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{1}^{\eta/4}\frac{e^{-\mu}}{\mu}d\mu\to-\intop_{0}^{1}\frac{e^{-\mu}}{\mu}d\mu
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{0}^{1}\frac{e^{-\mu}}{\mu}d\mu>\intop_{0}^{1}\frac{e^{-1}}{\mu}d\mu=\infty
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore this is NOT a sensible solution either.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another possibility is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x,y,t)=\frac{A}{t}\exp\left(-\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}}{4\kappa t}\right)+C
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to\infty$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{1}{t}\exp\left(-\frac{B}{t}\right)=\lim_{s\to0}\frac{s}{e^{Bs}}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,y,t)\to C$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to0$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{t\to0}\frac{1}{t}\exp\left(-\frac{B}{t}\right)=\lim_{s\to\infty}\frac{s}{e^{Bs}}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To have different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r,t)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to\infty$
\end_inset

, we need to superpose the above solution with another one.
 Using the method of separation of variables, we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(r,t)=\exp\left(-\lambda^{2}\kappa t\right)\cdot\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\left[EJ_{m}(\lambda r)+FY_{m}(\lambda r)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

are Bessel functions of the 1st and the 2nd kind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
3D Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 3D, the equation becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\kappa\nabla^{2}u & =\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}\\
\kappa\left(\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}}\right) & =\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=f(\eta)=f\left(\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}}{\kappa t}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}}{\kappa t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial x} & =\frac{2x}{\kappa t}f'(\eta)\\
\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}} & =\frac{4x^{2}}{\kappa^{2}t^{2}}f''(\eta)+\frac{2}{\kappa t}f'(\eta)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nabla^{2}u & =\frac{4}{\kappa^{2}t^{2}}\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}\right)f''(\eta)+\frac{6}{\kappa t}f'(\eta)\\
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t} & =f'(\eta)\cdot\left(-\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}}{\kappa t^{2}}\right)=-\frac{\eta}{t}f'(\eta)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The original equation becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-\frac{\eta}{t}f'(\eta) & =\frac{4}{\kappa t^{2}}\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}\right)f''(\eta)+\frac{6}{t}f'(\eta)\\
-\eta f'(\eta) & =4\eta f''(\eta)+6f'(\eta)\\
4\eta f''(\eta) & =-(\eta+6)f'(\eta)\\
\frac{1}{f'(\eta)}\frac{df'(\eta)}{d\eta} & =-\frac{\eta+6}{4\eta}\\
\frac{d}{d\eta}\ln\left|f'(\eta)\right| & =-\frac{\eta+6}{4\eta}\\
\ln\left|f'(\eta)\right| & =-\frac{1}{4}\eta-\frac{3}{2}\ln\eta+C\\
\left|f'(\eta)\right| & =\eta^{-3/2}e^{-\eta/4+C}\\
f'(\eta) & =A\eta^{-3/2}e^{-\eta/4}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(x,y,z,t)=f(\eta)=\intop_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}A\mu^{-3/2}e^{-\mu/4}d\mu+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are constants.
 To solve equation (1), we note
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(\eta) & =\intop_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}A\mu^{-3/2}e^{-\mu/4}d\mu+C\\
f(\eta) & =4A\intop_{\eta_{0}/4}^{\eta/4}\left(4\mu\right)^{-3/2}e^{-\mu}d\mu+C\\
f(\eta) & =\frac{A}{2}\intop_{\eta_{0}/4}^{\eta/4}\mu^{-3/2}e^{-\mu}d\mu+C
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integral diverges when 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to\infty,\eta\to0$
\end_inset

.
 So it does NOT represent a sensible solution, In other words, it does not
 satisfy the Dirichlet boundary condition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead seek a solution of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x,y,z,t)=f\left(\frac{z^{2}}{\kappa t}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then we'll again obtain the 1D solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u(z,t) & =\intop_{0}^{z^{2}/\kappa t}\frac{A}{\sqrt{\mu}}\exp\left(-\frac{\mu}{4}\right)d\mu+C\\
u(z,t) & =4A\intop_{0}^{z^{2}/4\kappa t}\left(4\mu\right)^{-1/2}e^{-\mu}d\mu+C\\
u(z,t) & =2A\intop_{0}^{z^{2}/4\kappa t}\mu^{-1/2}e^{-\mu}d\mu+C
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(z,t)\to2A\Gamma(1/2)+C=2A\sqrt{\pi}+C=T_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(z,t)\to C=T_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=-\frac{T_{\infty}-T_{0}}{2\sqrt{\pi}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(z,t)=-\frac{T_{\infty}-T_{0}}{\sqrt{\pi}}\intop_{0}^{z^{2}/4\kappa t}\mu^{-1/2}e^{-\mu}d\mu+T_{\infty}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

